# Searching and visualising the Royal Society Corpus

> In this notebook, we use
[`corpkit`](https://www.github.com/interrogator/corpkit)'s API to search the
RSC, to edit search results, and to visualise what we find.

## Setup

Below, we
import the `corpkit` module and instantiate our corpus:

```{.python .input  n=3}
%matplotlib inline
from corpkit import *
from corpkit.dictionaries import *
corpus = Corpus('rsc-annual-parsed')
```

```{.json .output n=3}

 {
  "name": "stdout",
  "output_type": "stream",
  "text": "Corpus: /Users/mahsa/Work/rsc/data/rsc-annual-parsed\n"
 }
]
```

The cells below show us how to interrogate the corpus. These interrogations can
take a while, however. Below, we can load the saved interrogations to save time:

```{.python .input  n=16}
lexicon = load('rsc-annual-parsed-lexicon')
part = load('rsc-annual-parsed-participants')
proc = load('rsc-annual-parsed-processes')
wc_fnc = load('rsc-annual-parsed-wc-fnc')
```

The corpus can be manipulated directly:

```{.python .input  n=4}
# sixth subcorpus
print(corpus.subcorpora[5])
# sixth subcorpus, third file, first sentence
print(corpus.subcorpora[5].files[2].document.loc[1])
# its parse tree
print(corpus.subcorpora[5].files[2].document._metadata[1]['parse'])
```

More importantly, it can be searched using the `interrogate()` method. A simple
interrogation involves picking what to search, and what to show. Below, we
search for any word, and show the word (i.e. make a lexicon).

```{.python .input  n=4}
# this is the default search: count words in each subcorpus
lexicon = corpus.interrogate(W, ANY, show=W)
# you can also just do corpus.lexicon
```

## Filtering data

The issue, however, is that this searches every sentence in
the corpus, which includes non-English, bad OCR, and so on. So, we might like to
instantiate the corpus while setting a filter on the `engprob` metadata, which
used `langdetect` to assign a probability that each text was English. Most
often, it assigned a probability of `1.0` to English documents, so we can use
that:

```{.python .input}
filt = {'engprob': '^1'}
corpus = Corpus('rsc-annual-parsed', just=filt)
corpus
```

There is still a lot of messy data, however. If we concordance a subcorpus, we
can see the problem:

```{.python .input}
# get just function matching root
conc = corpus[10].concordance(F, 'root')
conc
```

## Adding annotations through searching

To deal with this problem, we might
like to add a metadata tag to the sentences in the corpus whose root lemma is a
verb. Annotation requires that we switch `conc` to `True`.

> This tagging has
in fact already been done! It's shown here for educational purposes.

```{.python .input}
from corpkit.dictionaries.verblist import allverbs
# here, there are two search criteria: function and lemma
# by default, words are shown
v_root = corpus.interrogate({F: 'root', L: allverbs}, conc=True)
# add a new tag called verb_root
corpus.annotate(v_root, 'root_verb')
```

To protect the data a little, you need to turn off `dry_run` to actually
annotate the corpus:

```{.python .input}
corpus.annotate(v_root, 'root_verb', dry_run=False)
```

Adding a tag is nice, but we might like to actually add the verb itself as a
metadata field that we can use as a filter. To do that, we pass in a dict, with
the metadata field as the key, and 'm' (i.e. middle concordance column) as the
value.

```{.python .input}
corpus.annotate(v_root, {'root_verb': 'm'})
```

So, with this metadata added, we can create a second filter component:

```{.python .input  n=5}
filt = {'engprob': '^1', 'tags': 'root_verb'}
corpus = Corpus('rsc-annual-parsed', just=filt)
# we could have just added a single tag
#corpus.just['tags'] = 'root_verb'
```

```{.json .output n=5}
[
 {
  "name": "stdout",
  "output_type": "stream",
  "text": "Corpus: /Users/mahsa/Work/rsc/data/rsc-annual-parsed\n"
 }
]
```

Alright. Now we have a corpus and some useful filters in place. Let's get
searching!

## Deriving statistics

We can use these general frequencies to calculate
interesting stuff:

```{.python .input  n=10}
import pandas as pd
feat = corpus.features
derived = {'Characters per word': feat['Characters'] / feat['Words'],
           'Words per sentence': feat['Words'] / feat['Sentences'],
           'Words per clause': feat['Words'] / feat['Clauses'],
           'Clauses per sentence': feat['Clauses'] / feat['Sentences'],
           'Open class per closed class': feat['Open class'] / feat['Closed class'],
           'Passive per clause': feat['Passives'] / feat['Clauses']}
df = pd.DataFrame(derived)
df
```

plt = df.visualise()

## Participants and processes

We can use the dependency annotations to
approximate a distinction between participants and processes.

```{.python .input}
# thing is the head of the participant group
part = corpus.interrogate({F: roles.thing}, show=L)
part.save('participants')
```

```{.python .input}
# event is the head of the process group (the predicator)
# make sure the process is a known verb, too!
from corpkit.dictionaries.verblist import allverbs
proc = corpus.interrogate({F: roles.event, L: allverbs}, show=L)
proc.save('processes')
```

`corpkit` can calculate relative frequencies, and sort results based on their
trajectory:

```{.python .input  n=5}
rel_part_i = part.rel().sort('increase', keep_stats=True)
rel_part_d = rel_part_i.sort('reverse')
rel_proc_i = part.rel().sort('increase', keep_stats=True)
rel_proc_d = rel_proc_i.sort('reverse')
# show one of them
rel_proc_i.results
```

### Multiplotting

There is a `multiplot` method, which shows both subplots and
overall frequencies. To use it, we select a layout, which corresponds to the
number of subplots to show.

```{.python .input  n=8}
plt = rel_part_i.multiplot(layout=9)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
```

For greater control over the plots, we can pass in two dictionaries,
corresponding to the main plot and the subplots:

```{.python .input  n=11}
d1 = {'stacked': False, 'x_label': 'Year', 'y_label': 'Percentage of all results'}
d2 = {'grid': False}
plt = rel_part_d.multiplot(d1, d2, layout=9)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
```

Finally, it's possible to pass in different data for the main and the subplots.
Below, we show keyness vs. relative frequency:

```{.python .input  n=18}
keywds = part.keyness()
```

```{.python .input  n=26}
ents = ['result', 'effect', 'solution', 'he', 'you', 'they']
some_key = keywds.edit(just_entries=ents)
some_rel = rel_part_i.edit(just_entries=ents)
plt = some_key.multiplot({}, {'data': some_rel}, layout=6)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
```

So, let's plot our participants and processes, increasing and decreasing:

```{.python .input  n=14}
to_plot = [(rel_part_i, 'increasing', 'Participants'),
           (rel_proc_i, 'increasing', 'Processes'),
           (rel_part_d, 'decreasing', 'Participants'),
           (rel_proc_d, 'decreasing', 'Processes')]
for data, direction, name in to_plot:
    ylab = 'Percentage of all %s' % name
    title = '%s, %s' % (name, direction)
    plt = data.multiplot({'title': title, 'x_label': 'year', 'y_label': ylab}, layout=9)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
```

### Searching for feature pairs

So far, each time we've searched the corpus,
we've just outputted a single value, such as the lemma form, the word class or
the POS tag. We can get multiple values at the same time, however:

```{.python .input}
# get wordclass and dependency role
# pos is messy because of mistakes in NN/NNP annotation
wc_fnc = corpus.interrogate(show=[X, F])
```

```{.python .input  n=20}
wc_fnc_inc = wc_fnc.rel().sort('increase', keep_stats=True)
wc_fnc_dec = wc_fnc_inc.sort('reverse')
```

```{.python .input  n=21}
plt = wc_fnc_inc.visualise(subplots=True, layout=(2, 3))
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
```
